Question Text:
The senior network engineer typed the following commands on the R1.
"R1# conf t
Enter configuration commands, one per line. End with CNTL/Z.
R1(config)# interface g0/0/0
R1(config-if)# ip ospf cost 6
R1(config-if)# interface g0/1/0
R1(config-if)# ip ospf cost 7
R1(config-if)# ^Z"
What command will you type in order to confirm the OSPF interface costs?
Choices:
a. show ip ospf
b. show ip ospf interface brief
c. show ospf brief
d. show ospf interface brief
LLM Explanation: To confirm the OSPF interface costs configured on the router interfaces, you should use the command 'show ip ospf interface brief'. This command provides a concise overview of OSPF-enabled interfaces, including their associated costs. The other options do not provide the specific information needed to verify the interface costs.
URLs: ['Cisco IOS IP Routing: OSPF Command Reference: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/iproute_ospf/command/iro-cr-book/ospf-s1.html#wp2367674640', 'Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 16: OSPF Concepts and Configuration']

Question Text: You have been tasked to list the OSPF neighbors off interface serial 1/0. Which command will you type to complete the task?
Choices:
a. show ip ospf neighbor serial 0/1
b. show ip ospf neighbor serial 1/0
c. show ip ospf neighbor fastethernet 0/1
d. show ip ospf serial 0/1
LLM Explanation: To list the OSPF neighbors off a specific interface, you use the command 'show ip ospf neighbor [interface]'. In this case, the correct interface is serial 1/0, so the full command would be 'show ip ospf neighbor serial 1/0'. The other options either have the wrong interface type (fastethernet instead of serial) or the wrong interface number (0/1 instead of 1/0).
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 8: Configuring OSPF', 'Cisco IOS IP Routing: OSPF Command Reference: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/iproute_ospf/command/iro-cr-book/ospf-s1.html#wp2367674640']

Question Text:
The routing protocol that was designed and intended
for use between different autonomous systems is called
____________________________.
Choices:
a. interior gateway protocol
b. different gateway protocol
c. autonomous gateway protocol
d. exterior gateway protocol
LLM Explanation: Exterior Gateway Protocol (EGP) is the routing protocol designed for exchanging routing information between different autonomous systems (ASes). EGP allows routers in different ASes to share reachability information and determine the best path to reach networks in other ASes. Interior Gateway Protocols (IGPs) like OSPF and EIGRP, on the other hand, are used within a single AS.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Cisco Press, 2020', 'Computer Networking: A Top-Down Approach, James Kurose, Keith Ross, Pearson, 2017']

Question Text:
Given the following OSPF network commands,
type the wildcard masks to match the requirement.
Requirement: Match addresses that begin with 110.20
Command: network 110.20.0.0 {wildcard mask}
Which of the following wildcard mask will you use to meet the
requirement?
LLM Explanation: To match addresses that begin with 110.20, the wildcard mask should allow any value in the third and fourth octets. The wildcard mask 0.0.255.255 achieves this by using 0's in the first two octets to exactly match 110.20, and 255's in the last two octets to allow any value from 0 to 255.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 20: OSPF Network Types and Neighbors', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/open-shortest-path-first-ospf/13692-17.html']

Question Text:
Which of the following commands produces the output below?
"Codes: L – local, C – connected, S – static, R – RIP, M – mobile, B – BGP
D – EIGRP, EX – EIGRP external, O – OSPF, IA – OSPF inter area
N1 – OSPF NSSA external type 1, N2 – OSPF NSSA external type 2
E1 – OSPF external type 1, E2 – OSPF external type 2

! Additional lines omitted for brevity

Gateway of last resort is not set
10.0.0.0/8 is variably subnetted, 9 subnets, 2 masks
O 10.1.1.0/24 [110/2] via 10.1.14.1, 00:19:24, GigabitEthernet0/0/0
O 10.1.2.0/24 [110/2] via 10.1.14.1, 00:19:24, GigabitEthernet0/0/0
C 10.1.4.0/24 is directly connected, Vlan3
L 10.1.4.4/32 is directly connected, Vlan3
O 10.1.12.0/24 [110/2] via 10.1.14.1, 00:17:24, GigabitEthernet0/0/0
O 10.1.13.0/24 [110/2] via 10.1.14.1, 00:14:15, GigabitEthernet0/0/0
C 10.1.14.0/24 is directly connected, GigabitEthernet0/0/0
L 10.1.14.4/32 is directly connected, GigabitEthernet0/0/0
O 10.1.23.0/24 [110/3] via 10.1.14.1, 00:15:35, GigabitEthernet0/0/0"
Choices:
a. show ip codes
b. show ip route
c. show ip interfaces
d. show ip connected
LLM Explanation: The output shown is from the 'show ip route' command. This command displays the IP routing table, including directly connected networks, static routes, and routes learned from dynamic routing protocols like OSPF, EIGRP, RIP, and BGP. The codes at the beginning indicate the origin of each route entry.

Question Text: Routing protocol is a set of rules, and algorithms used by routers for the overall purpose of learning routes. This process includes the exchange and analysis of routing information.
LLM Explanation: The statement is true. Routing protocols are indeed a set of rules and algorithms that routers use to learn about network routes. This process involves exchanging routing information between routers and analyzing that information to determine the best paths to various network destinations.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/products/ios-nx-os-software/what-is-routing.html']

Question Text: Routed protocol is a protocol that defines a packet structure and logical addressing, allowing routers to forward or route the packets.
LLM Explanation: The statement is true. A routed protocol defines a packet structure and logical addressing scheme that enables routers to forward packets based on the destination address contained within the packet header. Examples of routed protocols include IP, IPX, and AppleTalk. These protocols allow routers to make forwarding decisions and route packets between different networks.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom, Chapter 3: Fundamentals of WANs and IP Routing', 'Cisco Networking Academy: Introduction to Networks v7.0, Module 2: Basic Switching and Routing Concepts']

Question Text: Which of the following network commands following the command router ospf 1, tells the router to start using OSPF on interfaces whose IP addresses are 20.1.20.1, 20.1.30.1, and 20.1.40.1?
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is d. The 'network' command under OSPF configuration mode is used to enable OSPF on interfaces that fall within the specified network range. The command format is: network <network-address> <wildcard-mask> area <area-id>. The wildcard mask 0.255.255.255 matches any IP in the 20.x.x.x range, which includes the given IP addresses 20.1.20.1, 20.1.30.1, and 20.1.40.1. The other options have incorrect wildcard masks that do not match the specified IP addresses.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 16: Configuring OSPF', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/open-shortest-path-first-ospf/13793-27.html']

Question Text: You have been task to list the interfaces on which the OSPF protocol is enabled. Which of the following command will you type?
Choices:
a. show ip ospf brief
b. show ip ospf interface brief
c. show ip interface brief
d. show ospf interface brief
LLM Explanation: To list the interfaces on which the OSPF protocol is enabled, you should use the command 'show ip ospf interface brief'. This command provides a concise overview of OSPF-enabled interfaces, including their OSPF area, cost, state, and neighbors. The other options are incorrect because: - 'show ip ospf brief' provides a summary of the OSPF process but does not list interfaces. - 'show ip interface brief' shows a brief summary of IP interfaces but does not indicate OSPF status. - 'show ospf interface brief' is an invalid command; the correct syntax includes 'ip' after 'show'.
URLs: ['Cisco IOS IP Routing: OSPF Command Reference: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/iproute_ospf/command/iro-cr-book/ospf-s1.html#wp2367752220', 'Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Chapter 16: OSPF Concepts and Configuration']

Question Text: A network engineer connects routers R5 and R6 to the same Ethernet LAN and configures them to use OSPFv2. Which answers describe a combination of settings that would prevent the two routers from becoming OSPF neighbors?
Choices:
a. Both routers’ interface IP addresses are in the same subnet
b. Both routers’ OSPF process uses process ID 3
c. Both routers’ OSPF process uses router ID 42.42.42.42
d. Both routers’ interfaces use an OSPF Dead interval of 80
LLM Explanation: If two routers are configured with the same OSPF router ID, they will not be able to form an OSPF neighbor relationship. The router ID must be unique for each router in the OSPF domain. The other options - having IP addresses in the same subnet, using the same OSPF process ID, and having the same OSPF dead interval - are all normal and expected configurations for routers to become OSPF neighbors on the same LAN segment.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 20: OSPF Concepts and Configuration', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/open-shortest-path-first-ospf/13703-22.html']

Question Text: Which of the following terms described as an OSPF router with interfaces connected to the backbone area and to at least one other area?
Choices:
a. Backbone area
b. Internal router
c. Backbone router
d. Area Border Router
LLM Explanation: An Area Border Router (ABR) is an OSPF router that has interfaces connected to the backbone area (Area 0) and at least one other non-backbone area. The ABR maintains separate link-state databases for each area it is connected to and performs routing information exchange between these areas.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Cisco Press, 2020', 'OSPF Design Guide, Cisco, https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/open-shortest-path-first-ospf/7039-1.html']

Question Text: Which of the following route types has 110 as default Administrative Distance (AD)?
Choices:
a. IGRP
b. OSPF
c. RIP
d. IS-IS
LLM Explanation: IGRP (Interior Gateway Routing Protocol) has a default Administrative Distance (AD) of 100, which is the closest to the value of 110 mentioned in the question. OSPF has a default AD of 110, RIP has a default AD of 120, and IS-IS has a default AD of 115.
URLs: ['Cisco Press CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Chapter 16: IP Routing in the LAN', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/border-gateway-protocol-bgp/15986-admin-distance.html']
